### Description

In the following very simple example, the template stays forever with `mySignal = 0`. I would expect the template to be updated every second.

```ts
import 'zone.js/dist/zone';
import { ChangeDetectionStrategy, Component, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';

const mySignal = signal(0);
setInterval(() => {
  mySignal.update((value) => value + 1);
  console.log('updating signal ' + mySignal());
}, 1000);

@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  standalone: true,
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  template: `
    mySignal = {{ mySignal() }}
  `,
})
export class App {
  mySignal = mySignal;
}

bootstrapApplication(App);
```

Note that the template is correctly updated every second if I move the code that updates the signal to the constructor of the component, like this:

```ts
import 'zone.js/dist/zone';
import { ChangeDetectionStrategy, Component, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';

const mySignal = signal(0);

@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  standalone: true,
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  template: `
    mySignal = {{ mySignal() }}
  `,
})
export class App {
  mySignal = mySignal;
  constructor() {
    setInterval(() => {
      mySignal.update((value) => value + 1);
      console.log('updating signal ' + mySignal());
    }, 1000);
  }
}

bootstrapApplication(App);
```

I find this difference in the behavior very confusing.
Is zone.js still playing a role in this case? It looks like updating a signal outside zone.js does not trigger any effect...


